			<!-- Begin News/Information Section -->
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" ID="Table23">
					<tr id="trmasthead">
						<td valign="middle" class="main_font" align="center">
							<font size="3"><b>&nbsp;</b></font>
					    </td>
					</tr>
					
					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Halfling Warrior</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:groghin97@hotmail.com">Garn</a> | 
		            9/14/1999 6:11:51 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">I am currently lvl 15 with my Halfling warrior, when creating him I tossed all my points into agi, wasn't a huge mistake, but I could have done with a lil less agi and a lil more str, to make amends I spent a good amount of cash and got a few str items like: bracer of erollisi(+5 str 2ac Lore item)a pair of +3 str earrings, and am currently working on getting some decent str rings, am holding out because they will be taking the place of my +5agi rings, which I will sorely miss... but if I get some good str rings it will be worth it.<BR>
<BR>
Now about that 2hs vs 1hs thing. In my opinion it equals out. You can either do bigger dmg slower, or lesser dmg faster. I'm talking weapons of equalness. if you get a 2hs that has major dmg compare it to two 1hs with high dmg. it will in my opinion equal out. on my warrior I started out by using pierceing, really fast delay, then when I got double attack at lvl 13 I picked up a Battle Axe 7dmg 35dly (I think anyhow, could be wrong on dly) I worked on my 1hs till I got double attack at lvl 15, then switched up for 2hs, which is what I am currently using.<BR>
As I said am lvl 15, I dumped a few points at trainer into 2hs so I wouldn't get my butt beat, cuz with only 1 in skill and such slow dly misses could mean your death or life. <BR>
<BR>
If you are thinking of starting a warrior I would say to equal out Str Agi and Dex as they are all important. Str may not seem to matter much at the beginning but later when you get heavy armor you are gonna wish you had more str (as I did). Agi helped me a lot, my base Agi with Halfling warrior was 125, I hardly get hit... very entertaining when you watch them miss you a lot. Dex is also important but not as much as Agi and Str, you are not going to suck horribly if you don't have the best Dex in the world, but keep in mind that missing the creatures a few times in a row can be real frustrating. <BR>
<BR>
Note: at about lvl 4 I would suggest maxing all your skills going against Fire Beetles, as they don't hit very hard and have a good amount of HP, Max your defense skill, offense skill, 1hs skill, 2hs skill, and an additional weapon skill if you want. maxing your Defense and Offense skills is a major must DO. Each time you raise them you will see a pt change in your persona, it adds up, if you are lvl 10, you have an average max of 55 in each skill, just think if you are 20pts behind in defense... you are missing out on a lot of AC... same goes for offense on your attack rating. I am speaking from experience, because it is really hard for me to build up my skill in 2hs and 1hs... I really wish I would have done it at lvl 4. as I said I used piercing to begin with, didn't pick up 1hs till lvl 13 and 2hs till lvl 15, easiest way is to max em out at lvl 4. Lucky for me I that I maxed defense and offense at lvl 4, just wish I would have had the foresight to have done 1hs and 2hs as well. Garn on Mithaniel Marr server.. oh and one more thing I played in Freeport instead of Rivervale, because it was familiar to me. doesn't matter where you play most areas have the same basic monsters for each zone.
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
